The Class of 2020 Graduation Parade and Ceremony will be LIVE STREAMED on Facebook by Kevin Webster and the Webster Sports Network! Tune in live at approximately 10:30am.

The parade starts at at 11am at Broad Street and travels south on Main Street then west on Front Street to the school. The ceremony commences immediately after the parade.

Click the link below for the Webster Sports Network. Like them in advance to get live notifications.

post_text:
Donation Request:
CHILD SIZED & ADULT SIZED FACE MASKS

Last week we passed out 70 bags of face masks to our students that were donated to our school. They went VERY quickly and we realized that there is a need for this life saving resource in our community.
We are asking for donations of face masks to hand out to our families. Disposable, reusable, handmade, bandanas, etc.

Donations can be delivered to the school on Tuesdays or Thursdays from 10-12 at the Elementary Door (off Maple St.) or mailed to the school at: 720 Front St. Greenport, NY 11944.

post_text:
Mr. Gamberg and Mr. Case delivered A FEW HUNDRED letters today that were personally addressed to the staff at Stony Brook Elih.

Greenport students and the students at Southold wrote to all employees as part of an initiative on the part of staff and students during the Spring break week to engage in "non-screen time" community service activities.

The employees at the hospital were very touched by the personal letters written to them by our students.

Way to go Porters!!!!

post_text:
Greenport schools has 15 3D printers running 12+ hours a day producing face masks and face shields for our hospitals and medical staff.

Our amazing Tech Teacher, Mr. Davies, is producing 36 face shields and and 20 reusable respirators each day!

From Mr. Davies on Friday: “We can run for a few more days at full capacity with the supply of 3mm filament.”

We need supplies! Can you help?
- 3mm pla or pet plastic filament
- thick sheet protectors
- PETT sheet material
- Elastic

post_text:
NOTICE TO PARENTS: We received a message this morning from the administration at Southold Schools that at approximately 7:40 am today, a high school student was approached by a middle-aged white male in a silver or light-gray minivan on Traveler Street by the Southold Library. He offered the student a ride to school. The student refused, proceeded to school, reported the incident, and is absolutely safe. The Southold Town Police were made aware immediately.

Please use this as an opportunity to discuss situations like this with your children.

Please know that student safety is of our utmost priority.

If you have any questions, please do not hesitate to contact the High School Office at (631) 477-1950 x.1225
